[268.277363, "o", "\r\n### ACT_MARKER: failure_verdict ###\r\n"]
[268.960112, "o", "--- AI verdict (bad-red canary) ---\r\n"]
[269.848124, "o", "promote:    false\r\nconfidence: 100\r\n\r\nAnalysis of the canary-demo rollout shows a critical functional regression. While the raw Kubernetes infrastructure events and cluster resource metrics (CPU and memory) indicate the system is operationally running and within normal resource limits, the actual application layer is severely degraded. The log analysis revealed that the stable pod processed traffic with 100% success (HTTP 200), whereas the newly deployed canary pod (running image 'argoproj/rollouts-demo:bad-red') experienced a massive, high-frequency wave of HTTP 500 Internal Server Errors shortly after startup. Because user-facing correctness and availability are the primary criteria for a successful rollout, a functional failure of this magnitude necessitates halting the rollout and performing a rollback.\r\n\r\n--- voting rationale ---\r\nThe specialist evaluations presented a 2-1 conflict. Both the Metrics Analyst and the Kubernetes Event Analyst voted to promote (true) since their respective domains (resource "]
[269.848436, "o", "consumption and Kubernetes container lifecycle events) showed no physical abnormalities or warning conditions. However, the Log Analyst strongly voted against promotion due to the high-frequency application-level HTTP 500 errors. As Lead Orchestrator, I resolved this conflict by giving precedence to application functional health and error rates over infrastructure-level health. An application that is running and consuming low resources but returning 500 errors to users is not a successful deployment. Therefore, the Log Analyst's vote was upheld, and the decision to rollback was made.\r\n"]
[277.885091, "o", "\r\n### ACT_MARKER: wrap_up ###\r\n"]
